# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: binomial-heap
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:binomial-heap/amortized-analysis] In computer science, **amortized analysis** is a method for analyzing a given algorithm's complexity, or how much of a resource, especially time or memory, it takes to execute.
[src:binomial-heap/amortized-analysis] The motivation for amortized analysis is that looking at the worst-case run time can be too pessimistic.
[src:binomial-heap/amortized-analysis] Instead, amortized analysis averages the running times of operations in a sequence over that sequence.
[src:binomial-heap/amortized-analysis] For a given operation of an algorithm, certain situations (e.g., input parametrizations or data structure contents) may imply a significant cost in resources, whereas other situations may not be as costly.
[src:binomial-heap/amortized-analysis] The amortized analysis considers both the costly and less costly operations together over the whole sequence of operations.
[src:binomial-heap/amortized-analysis] This may include accounting for different types of input, length of the input, and other factors that affect its performance.
[src:binomial-heap/amortized-analysis] Amortized analysis initially emerged from a method called aggregate analysis, which is now subsumed by amortized analysis.
[src:binomial-heap/amortized-analysis] The technique was first formally introduced by Robert Tarjan in his 1985 paper *Amortized Computational Complexity*, which addressed the need for a more useful form of analysis than the common probabilistic methods used.
[src:binomial-heap/amortized-analysis] Amortization was initially used for very specific types of algorithms, particularly those involving binary trees and union operations.
[src:binomial-heap/amortized-analysis] However, it is now ubiquitous and comes into play when analyzing many other algorithms as well.
[src:binomial-heap/amortized-analysis] Amortized analysis requires knowledge of which series of operations are possible.
[src:binomial-heap/amortized-analysis] This is most commonly the case with data structures, which have a state that persists between operations.
[src:binomial-heap/amortized-analysis] The basic idea is that a worst-case operation can alter the state in such a way that the worst case cannot occur again for a long time, thus "amortizing" its cost.
[src:binomial-heap/amortized-analysis] There are generally three methods for performing amortized analysis: the aggregate method, the accounting method, and the potential method.
[src:binomial-heap/amortized-analysis] All of these give correct answers; the choice of which to use depends on which is most convenient for a particular situation.
[src:binomial-heap/amortized-analysis] Consider a dynamic array that grows in size as more elements are added to it, such as `ArrayList` in Java or `std::vector` in C++.
[src:binomial-heap/amortized-analysis] If we started out with a dynamic array of size 4, we could push 4 elements onto it, and each operation would take constant time.
[src:binomial-heap/amortized-analysis] Yet pushing a fifth element onto that array would take longer as the array would have to create a new array of a scaled size, copy the old elements onto the new array, then add the new element.
[src:binomial-heap/amortized-analysis] The next few push operations would similarly take constant time, then the subsequent addition would require another slow scaling of the array size.
[src:binomial-heap/amortized-analysis] In general, for an arbitrary number n of pushes to an array of any initial size, the times for steps that scale the array add in a geometric series to $O(n)$ , while the constant times for each remaining push also add to $O(n)$ .
[src:binomial-heap/amortized-analysis] Therefore the average time per push operation is $O(n)/n=O(1)$ .
[src:binomial-heap/amortized-analysis] This reasoning can be formalized and generalized to more complicated data structures using amortized analysis.
[src:binomial-heap/amortized-analysis] The enqueue operation just pushes an element onto the input array; this operation does not depend on the lengths of either input or output and therefore runs in constant time.
[src:binomial-heap/amortized-analysis] However the dequeue operation is more complicated.
[src:binomial-heap/amortized-analysis] If the output array already has some elements in it, then dequeue runs in constant time; otherwise, dequeue takes ⁠ $O(n)$ ⁠ time to add all the elements onto the output array from the input array, where *n* is the current length of the input array.
[src:binomial-heap/amortized-analysis] After copying *n* elements from input, we can perform *n* dequeue operations, each taking constant time, before the output array is empty again.
[src:binomial-heap/amortized-analysis] Thus, we can perform a sequence of *n* dequeue operations in only ⁠ $O(n)$ ⁠ time, which implies that the amortized time of each dequeue operation is ⁠ $O(1)$ ⁠.
[src:binomial-heap/amortized-analysis] Alternatively, we can charge the cost of copying any item from the input array to the output array to the earlier enqueue operation for that item.
[src:binomial-heap/amortized-analysis] This charging scheme doubles the amortized time for enqueue but reduces the amortized time for dequeue to ⁠ $O(1)$ ⁠.
[src:binomial-heap/binomial-heap] In computer science, a **binomial heap** is a data structure that acts as a priority queue.
[src:binomial-heap/binomial-heap] It is an example of a mergeable heap (also called meldable heap), as it supports merging two heaps in logarithmic time.
[src:binomial-heap/binomial-heap] It is implemented as a heap similar to a binary heap but using a special tree structure that is different from the complete binary trees used by binary heaps.
[src:binomial-heap/binomial-heap] Binomial heaps were invented in 1978 by Jean Vuillemin.
[src:binomial-heap/binomial-heap] A binomial tree of order k has $2^{k}$ nodes, and height k .
[src:binomial-heap/binomial-heap] The name comes from the shape: a binomial tree of order k has ${\tbinom {k}{d}}$ nodes at depth d , a binomial coefficient.
[src:binomial-heap/binomial-heap] Because of its structure, a binomial tree of order k can be constructed from two trees of order $k-1$ by attaching one of them as the leftmost child of the root of the other tree.
[src:binomial-heap/binomial-heap] This feature is central to the *merge* operation of a binomial heap, which is its major advantage over other conventional heaps.
[src:binomial-heap/binomial-heap] The first property ensures that the root of each binomial tree contains the smallest key in the tree.
[src:binomial-heap/binomial-heap] It follows that the smallest key in the entire heap is one of the roots.
[src:binomial-heap/binomial-heap] The second property implies that a binomial heap with n nodes consists of at most $1+\log _{2}n$ binomial trees, where $\log _{2}$ is the binary logarithm.
[src:binomial-heap/binomial-heap] The number and orders of these trees are uniquely determined by the number of nodes n : there is one binomial tree for each nonzero bit in the binary representation of the number n .
[src:binomial-heap/binomial-heap] For example, the decimal number 13 is 1101 in binary, $2^{3}+2^{2}+2^{0}$ , and thus a binomial heap with 13 nodes will consist of three binomial trees of orders 3, 2, and 0 (see figure below).
[src:binomial-heap/binomial-heap] The number of different ways that n items with distinct keys can be arranged into a binomial heap equals the largest odd divisor of $n!$ .
[src:binomial-heap/binomial-heap] If the n items are inserted into a binomial heap in a uniformly random order, each of these arrangements is equally likely.
[src:binomial-heap/binomial-heap] Because no operation requires random access to the root nodes of the binomial trees, the roots of the binomial trees can be stored in a linked list, ordered by increasing order of the tree.
[src:binomial-heap/binomial-heap] These sibling pointers can be interpreted as the next pointers in a linked list of the children of each node, but with the opposite order from the linked list of roots: from largest to smallest order, rather than vice versa.
[src:binomial-heap/binomial-heap] This representation allows two trees of the same order to be linked together, making a tree of the next larger order, in constant time.
[src:binomial-heap/binomial-heap] The operation of **merging** two heaps is used as a subroutine in most other operations.
[src:binomial-heap/binomial-heap] A basic subroutine within this procedure merges pairs of binomial trees of the same order.
[src:binomial-heap/binomial-heap] This may be done by comparing the keys at the roots of the two trees (the smallest keys in both trees).
[src:binomial-heap/binomial-heap] To merge two heaps more generally, the lists of roots of both heaps are traversed simultaneously in a manner similar to that of the merge algorithm, in a sequence from smaller orders of trees to larger orders.
[src:binomial-heap/binomial-heap] When only one of the two heaps being merged contains a tree of order j , this tree is moved to the output heap.
[src:binomial-heap/binomial-heap] When both of the two heaps contain a tree of order j , the two trees are merged to one tree of order $j+1$ so that the minimum-heap property is satisfied.
[src:binomial-heap/binomial-heap] It may later become necessary to merge this tree with some other tree of order $j+1$ in one of the two input heaps.
[src:binomial-heap/binomial-heap] In the course of the algorithm, it will examine at most three trees of any order, two from the two heaps we merge and one composed of two smaller trees.
[src:binomial-heap/binomial-heap] Because each binomial tree in a binomial heap corresponds to a bit in the binary representation of its size, there is an analogy between the merging of two heaps and the binary addition of the *sizes* of the two heaps, from right-to-left.
[src:binomial-heap/binomial-heap] Whenever a carry occurs during addition, this corresponds to a merging of two binomial trees during the merge.
[src:binomial-heap/binomial-heap] Each binomial tree's traversal during merge only involves roots, hence making the time taken at most order $\log _{2}n$ and therefore the running time is $O(\log n)$ .
[src:binomial-heap/binomial-heap] A variant of the binomial heap, the skew binomial heap, achieves constant worst case insertion time by using forests whose tree sizes are based on the skew binary number system rather than on the binary number system.
[src:binomial-heap/binomial-heap] To find the **minimum** element of the heap, find the minimum among the roots of the binomial trees.
[src:binomial-heap/binomial-heap] This can be done in $O(\log n)$ time, as there are just $O(\log n)$ tree roots to examine.
[src:binomial-heap/binomial-heap] By using a pointer to the binomial tree that contains the minimum element, the time for this operation can be reduced to $O(1)$ .
[src:binomial-heap/binomial-heap] The pointer must be updated when performing any operation other than finding the minimum.
[src:binomial-heap/binomial-heap] This can be done in $O(\log n)$ time per update, without raising the overall asymptotic running time of any operation.
[src:binomial-heap/binomial-heap] To **delete the minimum element** from the heap, first find this element, remove it from the root of its binomial tree, and obtain a list of its child subtrees (which are each themselves binomial trees, of distinct orders).
[src:binomial-heap/binomial-heap] Transform this list of subtrees into a separate binomial heap by reordering them from smallest to largest order.
[src:binomial-heap/binomial-heap] Then merge this heap with the original heap.
[src:binomial-heap/binomial-heap] Since each root has at most $\log _{2}n$ children, creating this new heap takes time $O(\log n)$ .
[src:binomial-heap/binomial-heap] Merging heaps takes time $O(\log n)$ , so the entire delete minimum operation takes time $O(\log n)$ .
[src:binomial-heap/binomial-heap] After **decreasing** the key of an element, it may become smaller than the key of its parent, violating the minimum-heap property.
[src:binomial-heap/binomial-heap] If this is the case, exchange the element with its parent, and possibly also with its grandparent, and so on, until the minimum-heap property is no longer violated.
[src:binomial-heap/binomial-heap] Each binomial tree has height at most $\log _{2}n$ , so this takes $O(\log n)$ time.
[src:binomial-heap/binomial-heap] However, this operation requires that the representation of the tree include pointers from each node to its parent in the tree, somewhat complicating the implementation of other operations.
[src:binomial-heap/binomial-heap] To **delete** an element from the heap, decrease its key to negative infinity (or equivalently, to some value lower than any element in the heap) and then delete the minimum in the heap.
[src:binomial-heap/binomial-heap] Here are time complexities of various heap data structures.
[src:binomial-heap/binomial-heap] The abbreviation am. indicates that the given complexity is amortized, otherwise it is a worst-case complexity.
[src:binomial-heap/binomial-heap] For the meaning of "*O*(*f*)" and "*Θ*(*f*)" see Big O notation.
[src:binomial-heap/binomial-heap] For persistent heaps (not supporting *decrease-key*), a generic transformation reduces the cost of *meld* to that of *insert*, while the new cost of *delete-min* is the sum of the old costs of *delete-min* and *meld*.
[src:binomial-heap/binomial-heap] Here, it makes *meld* run in *Θ*(1) time (amortized, if the cost of *insert* is) while *delete-min* still runs in *O*(log *n*).
[src:binomial-heap/binomial-heap] Applied to skew binomial heaps, it yields Brodal-Okasaki queues, persistent heaps with optimal worst-case complexities.
[src:binomial-heap/binomial-heap] Brodal queues and strict Fibonacci heaps achieve optimal worst-case complexities for heaps.
[src:binomial-heap/binomial-heap] They were first described as imperative data structures.
[src:binomial-heap/binomial-heap] The Brodal-Okasaki queue is a persistent data structure achieving the same optimum, except that *decrease-key* is not supported.
[src:binomial-heap/brodal-queue] In computer science, the **Brodal queue** is a heap/priority queue structure with very low worst case time bounds: $O(1)$ for insertion, find-minimum, meld (merge two queues) and decrease-key and $O(\mathrm {log} (n))$ for delete-minimum and general deletion.
[src:binomial-heap/brodal-queue] They are the first heap variant to achieve these bounds without resorting to amortization of operational costs.
[src:binomial-heap/brodal-queue] Brodal queues are named after their inventor Gerth Stølting Brodal.
[src:binomial-heap/brodal-queue] While having better asymptotic bounds than other priority queue structures, they are, in the words of Brodal himself, "quite complicated" and "[not] applicable in practice." Brodal and Okasaki describe a persistent (purely functional) version of Brodal queues.
[src:binomial-heap/brodal-queue] A Brodal queue is a set of two trees $T_{1}$ and $T_{2}$ and 5 *guides*.
[src:binomial-heap/brodal-queue] The definition of the guide data structure can be found in the following section.
[src:binomial-heap/brodal-queue] For both trees, each node has a *rank*, this rank is useful for later operations and intuitively corresponds to the logarithm of the size of the subtree rooted in the node.
[src:binomial-heap/brodal-queue] We note ${\text{arity}}_{i}(x)$ the number of children of the node x with rank i .
[src:binomial-heap/brodal-queue] We will also use $t_{1}$ for the root of tree $T_{1}$ and $t_{2}$ for the root of tree $T_{2}$ .
[src:binomial-heap/brodal-queue] Here ${\text{NEXT-RANK-ARITY}}$ guarantees us that the size of the subtree rooted in a node is at least exponential to the rank of that node.
[src:binomial-heap/brodal-queue] In addition, ${\text{ARITY-BOUND}}$ bounds the number of children of each rank for a given node, this implies that all nodes have rank and degrees in $O(\log n)$ .
[src:binomial-heap/brodal-queue] In a Brodal queue, not every node will have a bigger value than its parent, the nodes vialoating this condition will be called *violating nodes*.
[src:binomial-heap/brodal-queue] However, we want to keep the number of *violating nodes* relatively small.
[src:binomial-heap/brodal-queue] To keep track of violating nodes, we create for each node two sets $V(x)$ and $W(x)$ of nodes larger than x .
[src:binomial-heap/brodal-queue] Intuitively, $V(x)$ are the nodes larger of x with large rank (such that $y\in V(x)$ if ${\text{rank}}(y)\geqslant {\text{rank}}(t_{1})$ ), and $W(x)$ are the nodes with small rank ( ${\text{rank}}(y)<{\text{rank}}(t_{1})$ ).
[src:binomial-heap/brodal-queue] These sets are implemented using doubly linked list meaning they have an order.
[src:binomial-heap/brodal-queue] In particular, all violating nodes added to $V(x)$ are added at the front of the list, and all violating nodes added to $W(x)$ are inserted next to a node of same rank.
[src:binomial-heap/brodal-queue] Since all nodes have rank in $O(\log n)$ the ${\text{W-RANK-BOUND}}$ and ${\text{V-RANK-BOUND}}$ , all $V(x)$ and $W(x)$ are in size $O(\log n)$ .
[src:binomial-heap/brodal-queue] We also have some invariants of the roots of the trees $T_{1}$ and $T_{2}$ : $t_{1}$ and $t_{2}$ (called the ${\text{ROOTS}}$ invariants).
[src:binomial-heap/brodal-queue] The ${\text{V-SIZE-BOUND}}$ invariant essentially tells us that if we increase the rank of $t_{1}$ by one, we have at most $\alpha$ new "large" violations (here large means having a high rank) without violating the ${\text{V-RANK-BOUND}}$ invariant.
[src:binomial-heap/brodal-queue] On the other hand, the ${\text{W-ELEMENTS-RANK}}$ invariant tells us that all violations in $W(x)$ are "small", this invariant is true per the definition of W .
[src:binomial-heap/brodal-queue] Maintaining the invariants ${\text{W-RANK-BOUND}}$ and ${\text{ROOT-ARITY}}$ is not trivial, to maintain these we will use the ${\text{DecreaseKey}}$ operation which can be implemented using a *guide* as defined in the next section.
[src:binomial-heap/brodal-queue] This definition is based on the definition from Brodal's paper.
[src:binomial-heap/brodal-queue] We assume that we have a sequence of variables $x_{k},\dots ,x_{1}$ and we want to make sure that $\forall i\leqslant k,x_{i}\leqslant T$ for some threshold T .
[src:binomial-heap/brodal-queue] The only operation allowed is ${\text{REDUCE}}(i)$ which decreases $x_{i}$ by at least 2 and increases $x_{i+1}$ by at most 1.
[src:binomial-heap/brodal-queue] We can assume without loss of generality that ${\text{REDUCE}}(i)$ reduces $x_{i}$ by 2 and increases $x_{i+1}$ by 1.
[src:binomial-heap/brodal-queue] If a $x_{j}$ is increased by one, the goal of the guide is to tell us on which indices i to apply ${\text{REDUCE}}(i)$ in order to respect the threshold.
[src:binomial-heap/brodal-queue] The guide is only allowed to make $O(1)$ calls to the ${\text{REDUCE}}$ function for each increase.
[src:binomial-heap/brodal-queue] As long as after the increase of $x_{j}$ we have $x_{j}\leqslant x'_{j}$ we do not need to ask help from our guide since $x_{j}$ is "far" bellow T .
[src:binomial-heap/brodal-queue] However, if $x_{j}=x'_{j}$ before the increase, then we have $x_{j}+1>x'_{j}$ after the change.
[src:binomial-heap/brodal-queue] To simplify the explanation, we can assume that $T=2$ , so that $x'_{i}\in \{0,1,2\}$ .
[src:binomial-heap/brodal-queue] The guide will create *blocks* in the sequence of $x'_{i}$ of form $2,1,1,\dots ,1,0$ where we allow there to be no 1 .
[src:binomial-heap/brodal-queue] The guide maintains the invariant that each element which isn't in a block is either a 1 or a 0 .
[src:binomial-heap/brodal-queue] For example, here are the blocks for a sequence of $x'_{i}$ .
[src:binomial-heap/brodal-queue] We can destroy a block in time $O(1)$ by assigning $\bot$ to the memory cell pointed to by each element of the block.
[src:binomial-heap/brodal-queue] This way, the guide is able to decide which indices to ${\text{REDUCE}}$ in time $O(1)$ .
[src:binomial-heap/brodal-queue] To reestablish the blocks, the pointers of the 1 and 0 added to the first block now point to the same cell as all the other elements from the first block, and the value of the second block's cell is changed to $\bot$ .
[src:binomial-heap/brodal-queue] In the previous example, only two ${\text{REDUCE}}$ operations were needed, this is actually the case for all instances.
[src:binomial-heap/brodal-queue] Therefore, the queue only needs $O(1)$ operations to reestablish the property.
[src:binomial-heap/brodal-queue] To implement the different priority queue operations we first need to describe some essential transformations for the trees.
[src:binomial-heap/brodal-queue] To link trees, we need three nodes $x_{1},x_{2}{\text{ and }}x_{3}$ of equal rank.
[src:binomial-heap/brodal-queue] We can calculate the minimum of these three nodes with two comparisons.
[src:binomial-heap/brodal-queue] Here we assume that $x_{1}$ is the minimum but the process is similar for all $x_{i}$ .
[src:binomial-heap/brodal-queue] We can now make the nodes $x_{2}$ and $x_{3}$ the two leftmost sons of $x_{1}$ and increase the rank of $x_{1}$ by one.
[src:binomial-heap/brodal-queue] This preserves all the ${\text{RANK}}$ and ${\text{SETS}}$ invariants.
[src:binomial-heap/brodal-queue] If x has exactly two or three sons of rank ${\text{rank}}(x)-1$ , we can remove these sons and x gets the rank of its new largest son plus one.
[src:binomial-heap/brodal-queue] From the ${\text{ARITY-BOUND}}$ condition, we know that that the ${\text{NEXT-RANK-ARITY}}$ invariant will be preserved.
[src:binomial-heap/brodal-queue] Then, all the ${\text{RANK}}$ and ${\text{SETS}}$ invariants remain satisfied.
[src:binomial-heap/brodal-queue] If x has 4 or more children, we can simply cut of two of them and all the invariants remain true.
[src:binomial-heap/brodal-queue] Therefore, the delinking of a tree of rank k will always result in two or three trees of rank $k-1$ (from the 2 or 3 children cut off) and one additional tree of rank at most k .
[src:binomial-heap/brodal-queue] When we add and remove sons of a root, we want to keep the ${\text{ROOT-RANK}}$ invariant true.
[src:binomial-heap/brodal-queue] For this purpose, we use 4 guides, two for each roots $t_{1}$ and $t_{2}$ .
[src:binomial-heap/brodal-queue] To have constant time access to the son of $t_{1}$ we create an extendible array of pointed that has for each rank $i\in \{0,\dots ,{\text{rank}}(t_{1})-1\}$ a pointer to a son of $t_{1}$ of rank i .
[src:binomial-heap/brodal-queue] The sons of $t_{1}$ of rank ${\text{rank}}(t_{1})-1$ and ${\text{rank}}(t_{1})-2$ are treated separately in a straight forward way to maintant their number between 2 and 7.
[src:binomial-heap/brodal-queue] The equivalent to the $x'_{i}$ variable in the definition of the guide will have the values $\{5,6,7\}$ for the higher bound guide and $\{4,3,2\}$ for the lower bound.
[src:binomial-heap/brodal-queue] In this context, when we add a child of rank i to the root, we increase $x'_{i}$ by one, and apply the ${\text{REDUCE}}$ operations.
[src:binomial-heap/brodal-queue] The ${\text{RECUCE}}(i)$ operation here consists of linking three trees of rank i which creates a new child of rank $i+1$ .
[src:binomial-heap/brodal-queue] If this increase results in too many sons of rank ${\text{rank}}(t_{1})-2$ or ${\text{rank}}(t_{1})-1$ we link some of these sons together and possibly increase the rank of $t_{1}$ .
[src:binomial-heap/brodal-queue] If we increase the rank of $t_{1}$ , we have to increase the length of the extendible array managed by the guides.
[src:binomial-heap/brodal-queue] Cutting off a son from $t_{1}$ is very similar, except here the ${\text{REDUCE}}$ operation corresponds to the delinking of a tree.
[src:binomial-heap/brodal-queue] For the root $t_{2}$ the situation is nearly the same.
[src:binomial-heap/brodal-queue] However, since ${\text{MINIMUM-NODE}}$ guarantees us that $t_{1}$ is the minimum element, we know that we won't create any violation by linking or delinking children of $t_{1}$ .
[src:binomial-heap/brodal-queue] Linking sons will never create new violations but the delinking of sons can create up to three new violations.
[src:binomial-heap/brodal-queue] The tree left over by a delinking is made a son of $t_{1}$ if it has rank less than ${\text{rank}}(t_{1})$ and otherwise it becomes a son of $t_{2}$ .
[src:binomial-heap/brodal-queue] The new violations which have rank larger than ${\text{rank}}(t_{1})$ are added to $V(t_{1})$ .
[src:binomial-heap/brodal-queue] To maintain the invariants on the $V(t_{1})$ set (namely ${\text{V-RANK-BOUND}}$ and ${\text{V-SIZE-BOUND}}$ ), we have to guarantee that the rank of $t_{1}$ will be increased and that $\alpha$ in those invariants is chosen large enough.
[src:binomial-heap/brodal-queue] The goal of this transformation is to reduce the total amount of potential violations, meaning reducing $\left|\bigcup _{x\in T_{1}\cup T_{2}}V(x)\cup W(x)\right|$ .
[src:binomial-heap/brodal-queue] We assume we have two potential violations $x_{1}$ and $x_{2}$ of equal rank k .
[src:binomial-heap/brodal-queue] Because of ${\text{ARITY-BOUND}}$ , we know that both $x_{1}$ and $x_{2}$ have at least one brother.
[src:binomial-heap/brodal-queue] Else, $x_{1}$ and $x_{2}$ are brothers of a node we will call y .
[src:binomial-heap/brodal-queue] Else, $x_{1}$ and $x_{2}$ are the only children of rank k of y ..
[src:binomial-heap/brodal-queue] We will cut off $x_{1},x_{2}{\text{ and }}y$ , the new rank of y will be one plus the rank of its leftmost son, We replace y by a son on $t_{1}$ of rank $k+1$ , which can be cut off as described in the previous subsection.
[src:binomial-heap/brodal-queue] If the replacement for y becomes a violating node of rank $k+1$ , we add it to $W(t_{1})$ .
[src:binomial-heap/brodal-queue] Finally we make $x_{1},x_{2}{\text{ and }}y$ new sons of $t_{1}$ as described above.
[src:binomial-heap/brodal-queue] The only violation sets where we will add violations are $V(t_{1})$ and $W(t_{1})$ .
[src:binomial-heap/brodal-queue] As described above, the invariants on those sets are maintained using guides.
[src:binomial-heap/brodal-queue] If there are more than 4 violations which are sons of $t_{2}$ , we cut the additional violations off and link them below $t_{1}$ .
[src:binomial-heap/brodal-queue] This removes the violation created by these nodes and doesn't affect the guide maintaining the sons of $t_{2}$ .
[src:binomial-heap/brodal-queue] For each priority queue operation that is performed, we increase the rank of $t_{1}$ by at least one by moving a constant number of sons of $t_{2}$ to $t_{1}$ (provided that $T_{2}\neq \emptyset$ ).
[src:binomial-heap/brodal-queue] Increasing the rank of $t_{1}$ allows us to add violations to $V(t_{1})$ while still maintaining all our invariants.
[src:binomial-heap/brodal-queue] Otherwise, we cut off a son of $t_{2}$ of rank ${\text{rank}}(t_{1})+2$ , delink this son and add the resulting trees to $t_{1}$ .
[src:binomial-heap/brodal-queue] If $T_{2}=\emptyset$ , we know that $t_{1}$ is the node of largest rank, therefore we know that no large violations can be created.
[src:binomial-heap/brodal-queue] ${\text{MakeQueue}}()$ just returns a pair of empty trees.
[src:binomial-heap/brodal-queue] The tree having the minimum root becomes the new $T_{1}$ tree.
[src:binomial-heap/brodal-queue] If this tree is also the tree of maximum rank, we can add all the other trees below as described previously.
[src:binomial-heap/brodal-queue] In this case, no violating node is created so no transformation is done on violating nodes.
[src:binomial-heap/brodal-queue] Otherwise, the tree of maximum rank becomes the new $T_{2}$ tree and the other trees are added below as described in the section "Maintaining the sons of a root".
[src:binomial-heap/brodal-queue] If some trees have equal rank to this new $T_{2}$ , we can delink them before adding them.
[src:binomial-heap/brodal-queue] The violations created are handled as explained in the section : "Avoiding too many violations".
[src:binomial-heap/brodal-queue] ${\text{DecreaseKey}}(Q,e,e')$ replaces the element of e by $e'$ (with $e'\leqslant e$ ).
[src:binomial-heap/brodal-queue] If $e'<t_{1}$ , we swap the two nodes, otherwise, we handle the potential new violation as explained in the section "Avoiding too many violations".
[src:binomial-heap/brodal-queue] ${\text{DeleteMin}}(Q)$ is allowed to take worst case time $O(\log n)$ .
[src:binomial-heap/brodal-queue] First, we completely empty $T_{2}$ by moving all the sons of $t_{2}$ to $t_{1}$ then making $t_{2}$ a rank 0 son of $t_{1}$ .
[src:binomial-heap/brodal-queue] Then, $t_{1}$ is deleted, this leaves us with at most $O(\log n)$ independent trees.
[src:binomial-heap/brodal-queue] The new minimum is then found by looking at the violating sets of the old root and looking at all the roots of the new trees.
[src:binomial-heap/brodal-queue] If the minimum element is not a root, we can swap a root from a tree of equal rank to it.
[src:binomial-heap/brodal-queue] Then, we make the independent trees sons of the new minimum element by performing $O(\log n)$ linking and delinking operations.
[src:binomial-heap/brodal-queue] This reestablishes the ${\text{RANK}}$ and ${\text{ROOTS}}$ invariants.
[src:binomial-heap/brodal-queue] By merging the V and W sets of the new root along with the V and W sets of the old root together, we get one new violation set of size $O(\log n)$ .
[src:binomial-heap/brodal-queue] By doing at most $O(\log n)$ violation reducing transformations we can make the violation set only contain at most one element of each rank.
[src:binomial-heap/brodal-queue] This set will be our new W set and the new V set is empty.
[src:binomial-heap/brodal-queue] This reestablishes the ${\text{SETS}}$ invariants.
[src:binomial-heap/brodal-queue] We also have to initialise a new guide for the new root $t_{1}$ .
[src:binomial-heap/brodal-queue] Here, $-\infty$ denotes the smallest possible element. ${\text{Delete}}(Q,e)$ can simply be implemented by calling ${\text{DecreaseKey}}(Q,e,-\infty )$ followed by ${\text{DeleteMin}}(Q)$ .
[src:binomial-heap/brodal-queue] In this section, we summarize some implementation details for the Brodal Queue data structure.
[src:binomial-heap/brodal-queue] Due to its high amount of pointers and sets to keep track of, the Brodal Queue is extremely hard to implement.
[src:binomial-heap/brodal-queue] For this reason it is best described as a purely theoretical object to lower time complexity on algorithms like Dijkstra's algorithm.
[src:binomial-heap/brodal-queue] However, the Brodal has been implemented in Scala (the GitHub repository can be found here: https://github.com/ruippeixotog/functional-brodal-queues).
[src:binomial-heap/brodal-queue] In his paper, Gerth Stølting Brodal mentions that: "An important issue for further work is to simplify the construction to make it applicable in practice".
[src:binomial-heap/brodal-queue] Gerth Stølting Brodal is a professor at the University of Aarhus, Denmark.
[src:binomial-heap/fibonacci-heap] In computer science, a **Fibonacci heap** is a data structure for priority queue operations, consisting of a collection of heap-ordered trees.
[src:binomial-heap/fibonacci-heap] It has a better amortized running time than many other priority queue data structures including the binary heap and binomial heap.
[src:binomial-heap/fibonacci-heap] Tarjan developed Fibonacci heaps in 1984 and published them in a scientific journal in 1987.
[src:binomial-heap/fibonacci-heap] Fibonacci heaps are named after the Fibonacci numbers, which are used in their running time analysis.
[src:binomial-heap/fibonacci-heap] The amortized times of all operations on Fibonacci heaps is constant, except *delete-min*.
[src:binomial-heap/fibonacci-heap] Deleting an element (most often used in the special case of deleting the minimum element) works in $O(\log n)$ amortized time, where n is the size of the heap.
[src:binomial-heap/fibonacci-heap] This means that starting from an empty data structure, any sequence of *a* insert and *decrease-key* operations and *b* *delete-min* operations would take $O(a+b\log n)$ worst case time, where n is the maximum heap size.
[src:binomial-heap/fibonacci-heap] In a binary or binomial heap, such a sequence of operations would take $O((a+b)\log n)$ time.
[src:binomial-heap/fibonacci-heap] A Fibonacci heap is thus better than a binary or binomial heap when b is smaller than a by a non-constant factor.
[src:binomial-heap/fibonacci-heap] It is also possible to merge two Fibonacci heaps in constant amortized time, improving on the logarithmic merge time of a binomial heap, and improving on binary heaps which cannot handle merges efficiently.
[src:binomial-heap/fibonacci-heap] Using Fibonacci heaps improves the asymptotic running time of algorithms which utilize priority queues.
[src:binomial-heap/fibonacci-heap] For example, Dijkstra's algorithm and Prim's algorithm can be made to run in $O(|E|+|V|\log |V|)$ time.
[src:binomial-heap/fibonacci-heap] A Fibonacci heap is a collection of trees satisfying the minimum-heap property, that is, the key of a child is always greater than or equal to the key of the parent.
[src:binomial-heap/fibonacci-heap] This implies that the minimum key is always at the root of one of the trees.
[src:binomial-heap/fibonacci-heap] Compared with binomial heaps, the structure of a Fibonacci heap is more flexible.
[src:binomial-heap/fibonacci-heap] The trees do not have a prescribed shape and in the extreme case the heap can have every element in a separate tree.
[src:binomial-heap/fibonacci-heap] This flexibility allows some operations to be executed in a lazy manner, postponing the work for later operations.
[src:binomial-heap/fibonacci-heap] For example, merging heaps is done simply by concatenating the two lists of trees, and operation *decrease key* sometimes cuts a node from its parent and forms a new tree.
[src:binomial-heap/fibonacci-heap] However, at some point order needs to be introduced to the heap to achieve the desired running time.
[src:binomial-heap/fibonacci-heap] In particular, degrees of nodes (here degree means the number of direct children) are kept quite low: every node has degree at most $\log n$ and the size of a subtree rooted in a node of degree k is at least $F_{k+2}$ , where $F_{i}$ is the i th Fibonacci number.
[src:binomial-heap/fibonacci-heap] This is achieved by the rule: at most one child can be cut off each non-root node.
[src:binomial-heap/fibonacci-heap] When a second child is cut, the node itself needs to be cut from its parent and becomes the root of a new tree (see Proof of degree bounds, below).
[src:binomial-heap/fibonacci-heap] The number of trees is decreased in the operation *delete-min*, where trees are linked together.
[src:binomial-heap/fibonacci-heap] As a result of a relaxed structure, some operations can take a long time while others are done very quickly.
[src:binomial-heap/fibonacci-heap] For the amortized running time analysis, we use the potential method, in that we pretend that very fast operations take a little bit longer than they actually do.
[src:binomial-heap/fibonacci-heap] This additional time is then later combined and subtracted from the actual running time of slow operations.
[src:binomial-heap/fibonacci-heap] The amount of time saved for later use is measured at any given moment by a potential function.
[src:binomial-heap/fibonacci-heap] The potential $\phi$ of a Fibonacci heap is given by $\phi =t+2m,$ where t is the number of trees in the Fibonacci heap, and m is the number of marked nodes.
[src:binomial-heap/fibonacci-heap] A node is marked if at least one of its children was cut, since this node was made a child of another node (all roots are unmarked).
[src:binomial-heap/fibonacci-heap] The amortized time for an operation is given by the sum of the actual time and c times the difference in potential, where *c* is a constant (chosen to match the constant factors in the big O notation for the actual time).
[src:binomial-heap/fibonacci-heap] Thus, the root of each tree in a heap has one unit of time stored.
[src:binomial-heap/fibonacci-heap] This unit of time can be used later to link this tree with another tree at amortized time 0.
[src:binomial-heap/fibonacci-heap] Also, each marked node has two units of time stored.
[src:binomial-heap/fibonacci-heap] One can be used to cut the node from its parent.
[src:binomial-heap/fibonacci-heap] If this happens, the node becomes a root and the second unit of time will remain stored in it as in any other root.
[src:binomial-heap/fibonacci-heap] To allow fast deletion and concatenation, the roots of all trees are linked using a circular doubly linked list.
[src:binomial-heap/fibonacci-heap] The children of each node are also linked using such a list.
[src:binomial-heap/fibonacci-heap] For each node, we maintain its number of children and whether the node is marked.
[src:binomial-heap/fibonacci-heap] We maintain a pointer to the root containing the minimum key, allowing $O(1)$ access to the minimum.
[src:binomial-heap/fibonacci-heap] This pointer must be updated during the other operations, which adds only a constant time overhead.
[src:binomial-heap/fibonacci-heap] The merge operation simply concatenates the root lists of two heaps together and sets the minimum to be the smaller of the two heaps.
[src:binomial-heap/fibonacci-heap] This can be done in constant time, and the potential does not change, leading again to constant amortized time.
[src:binomial-heap/fibonacci-heap] The insertion operation can be considered a special case of the merge operation, with a single node.
[src:binomial-heap/fibonacci-heap] The node is simply appended to the root list, increasing the potential by one.
[src:binomial-heap/fibonacci-heap] The amortized cost is thus still constant.
[src:binomial-heap/fibonacci-heap] The delete-min operation does most of the work in restoring the structure of the heap.
[src:binomial-heap/fibonacci-heap] We therefore decrease the number of roots by successively linking together roots of the same degree.
[src:binomial-heap/fibonacci-heap] When two roots have the same degree, we make the one with the larger key a child of the other, so that the minimum heap property is conserved.
[src:binomial-heap/fibonacci-heap] The degree of the smaller root increases by one.
[src:binomial-heap/fibonacci-heap] This is repeated until every root has a different degree.
[src:binomial-heap/fibonacci-heap] To find trees of the same degree efficiently, we use an array of length $O(\log n)$ in which we keep a pointer to one root of each degree.
[src:binomial-heap/fibonacci-heap] When a second root is found of the same degree, the two are linked and the array is updated.
[src:binomial-heap/fibonacci-heap] The actual running time is $O(\log n+m)$ , where m is the number of roots at the beginning of the second phase.
[src:binomial-heap/fibonacci-heap] In the end, we will have at most $O(\log n)$ roots (because each has a different degree).
[src:binomial-heap/fibonacci-heap] Therefore, the difference in the potential from before to after this phase is $O(\log n)-m$ .
[src:binomial-heap/fibonacci-heap] Thus, the amortized running time is $O(\log n+m)+c(O(\log n)-m)$ .
[src:binomial-heap/fibonacci-heap] By choosing a sufficiently large c such that the terms in m cancel out, this simplifies to $O(\log n)$ .
[src:binomial-heap/fibonacci-heap] Search the final list of roots to find the minimum, and update the minimum pointer accordingly.
[src:binomial-heap/fibonacci-heap] This takes $O(\log n)$ time, because the number of roots has been reduced.
[src:binomial-heap/fibonacci-heap] Overall, the amortized time of this operation is $O(\log n)$ , provided that $d=O(\log n)$ .
[src:binomial-heap/fibonacci-heap] The proof of this is given in the following section.
[src:binomial-heap/fibonacci-heap] If decreasing the key of a node x causes it to become smaller than its parent, then it is cut from its parent, becoming a new unmarked root.
[src:binomial-heap/fibonacci-heap] If it is also less than the minimum key, then the minimum pointer is updated.
[src:binomial-heap/fibonacci-heap] We then initiate a series of *cascading cuts*, starting with the parent of x .
[src:binomial-heap/fibonacci-heap] As long as the current node is marked, it is cut from its parent and made an unmarked root.
[src:binomial-heap/fibonacci-heap] This process stops when we reach an unmarked node y .
[src:binomial-heap/fibonacci-heap] In this process we introduce some number, say k , of new trees.
[src:binomial-heap/fibonacci-heap] Except possibly x , each of these new trees loses its original mark.
[src:binomial-heap/fibonacci-heap] The terminating node y may become marked.
[src:binomial-heap/fibonacci-heap] Therefore, the change in the number of marked nodes is between of $-k$ and $-k+2$ .
[src:binomial-heap/fibonacci-heap] The resulting change in potential is $k+2(-k+2)=-k+4$ .
[src:binomial-heap/fibonacci-heap] The actual time required to perform the cutting was $O(k)$ .
[src:binomial-heap/fibonacci-heap] Hence, the amortized time is $O(k)+c(-k+4)$ , which is constant, provided c is sufficiently large.
[src:binomial-heap/fibonacci-heap] The amortized performance of a Fibonacci heap depends on the degree (number of children) of any tree root being $O(\log n)$ , where n is the size of the heap.
[src:binomial-heap/fibonacci-heap] Here we show that the size of the (sub)tree rooted at any node x of degree d in the heap must have size at least $F_{d+2}$ , where $F_{i}$ is the i th Fibonacci number.
[src:binomial-heap/fibonacci-heap] The degree bound follows from this and the fact (easily proved by induction) that $F_{d+2}\geq \varphi ^{d}$ for all integers $d\geq 0$ , where $\varphi =(1+{\sqrt {5}})/2\approx 1.618$ is the golden ratio.
[src:binomial-heap/fibonacci-heap] We then have $n\geq F_{d+2}\geq \varphi ^{d}$ , and taking the log to base $\varphi$ of both sides gives $d\leq \log _{\varphi }n$ as required.
[src:binomial-heap/fibonacci-heap] Let x be an arbitrary node in a Fibonacci heap, not necessarily a root.
[src:binomial-heap/fibonacci-heap] Define $\mathrm {size} (x)$ to be the size of the tree rooted at x (the number of descendants of x , including x itself).
[src:binomial-heap/fibonacci-heap] We prove by induction on the height of x (the length of the longest path from x to a descendant leaf) that $\mathrm {size} (x)\geq F_{d+2}$ , where d is the degree of x .
[src:binomial-heap/fibonacci-heap] We claim that $c_{i}\geq i-2$ for each i .
[src:binomial-heap/fibonacci-heap] Just before $y_{i}$ was made a child of x , $y_{1}\dots y_{i-1}$ were already children of x , and so x must have had degree at least $i-1$ at that time.
[src:binomial-heap/fibonacci-heap] Since trees are combined only when the degrees of their roots are equal, it must have been the case that $y_{i}$ also had degree at least $i-1$ at the time when it became a child of x .
[src:binomial-heap/fibonacci-heap] From that time to the present, $y_{i}$ could have only lost at most one child (as guaranteed by the marking process), and so its current degree $c_{i}$ is at least $i-2$ .
[src:binomial-heap/fibonacci-heap] This gives the desired lower bound on $\mathrm {size} (x)$ .
[src:binomial-heap/fibonacci-heap] They are not as efficient in practice when compared with theoretically less efficient forms of heaps.
[src:binomial-heap/fibonacci-heap] In their simplest version, they require manipulation of four pointers per node, whereas only two or three pointers per node are needed in other structures, such as the binomial heap, or pairing heap.
[src:binomial-heap/fibonacci-heap] This results in large memory consumption per node and high constant factors on all operations.
[src:binomial-heap/fibonacci-heap] Although the total running time of a sequence of operations starting with an empty structure is bounded by the bounds given above, some (very few) operations in the sequence can take very long to complete (in particular, delete-min has linear running time in the worst case).
[src:binomial-heap/fibonacci-heap] For this reason, Fibonacci heaps and other amortized data structures may not be appropriate for real-time systems.
[src:binomial-heap/fibonacci-heap] It is possible to create a data structure which has the same worst-case performance as the Fibonacci heap has amortized performance.
[src:binomial-heap/fibonacci-heap] One such structure, the Brodal queue, is, in the words of the creator, "quite complicated" and "[not] applicable in practice." Invented in 2012, the strict Fibonacci heap is a simpler (compared to Brodal's) structure with the same worst-case bounds.
[src:binomial-heap/fibonacci-heap] Despite being simpler, experiments show that in practice the strict Fibonacci heap performs slower than more complicated Brodal queue and also slower than basic Fibonacci heap.
[src:binomial-heap/fibonacci-heap] The run-relaxed heaps of Driscoll et al. give good worst-case performance for all Fibonacci heap operations except merge.
[src:binomial-heap/fibonacci-heap] Recent experimental results suggest that the Fibonacci heap is more efficient in practice than most of its later derivatives, including quake heaps, violation heaps, strict Fibonacci heaps, and rank pairing heaps, but less efficient than pairing heaps or array-based heaps.
[src:binomial-heap/heap-data-structure] In computer science, a **heap** is a tree-based data structure that satisfies the **heap property**: In a *max heap*, for any given node C, if P is the parent node of C, then the *key* (the *value*) of P is greater than or equal to the key of C.
[src:binomial-heap/heap-data-structure] In a *min heap*, the key of P is less than or equal to the key of C.
[src:binomial-heap/heap-data-structure] The node at the "top" of the heap (with no parents) is called the *root* node.
[src:binomial-heap/heap-data-structure] The heap is one maximally efficient implementation of an abstract data type called a priority queue, and in fact, priority queues are often referred to as "heaps", regardless of how they may be implemented.
[src:binomial-heap/heap-data-structure] In a heap, the highest (or lowest) priority element is always stored at the root.
[src:binomial-heap/heap-data-structure] However, a heap is not a sorted structure; it can be regarded as being partially ordered.
[src:binomial-heap/heap-data-structure] A heap is a useful data structure when it is necessary to repeatedly remove the object with the highest (or lowest) priority, or when insertions need to be interspersed with removals of the root node.
[src:binomial-heap/heap-data-structure] A common implementation of a heap is the binary heap, in which the tree is a complete binary tree (see figure).
[src:binomial-heap/heap-data-structure] The heap data structure, specifically the binary heap, was introduced by J.
[src:binomial-heap/heap-data-structure] Williams in 1964, as a data structure for the heapsort sorting algorithm.
[src:binomial-heap/heap-data-structure] Heaps are also crucial in several efficient graph algorithms such as Dijkstra's algorithm.
[src:binomial-heap/heap-data-structure] When a heap is a complete binary tree, it has the smallest possible height—a heap with *N* nodes and *a* branches for each node always has log*a* *N* height.
[src:binomial-heap/heap-data-structure] Note that, as shown in the graphic, there is no implied ordering between siblings or cousins and no implied sequence for an in-order traversal (as there would be in, e.g., a binary search tree).
[src:binomial-heap/heap-data-structure] The heap relation mentioned above applies only between nodes and their parents, grandparents.
[src:binomial-heap/heap-data-structure] The maximum number of children each node can have depends on the type of heap.
[src:binomial-heap/heap-data-structure] Heaps are typically constructed in-place in the same array where the elements are stored, with their structure being implicit in the access pattern of the operations.
[src:binomial-heap/heap-data-structure] Heaps differ in this way from other data structures with similar or in some cases better theoretic bounds such as radix trees in that they require no additional memory beyond that used for storing the keys.
[src:binomial-heap/heap-data-structure] For a binary heap, in the array, the first index contains the root element.
[src:binomial-heap/heap-data-structure] The next two indices of the array contain the root's children.
[src:binomial-heap/heap-data-structure] The next four indices contain the four children of the root's two child nodes, and so on.
[src:binomial-heap/heap-data-structure] Therefore, given a node at index i, its children are at indices ⁠ $2i+1$ ⁠ and ⁠ $2i+2$ ⁠, and its parent is at index ⌊(*i*−1)/2⌋ in an array starting from index ⁠ 0 ⁠, or at ⁠ $2i$ ⁠, ⁠ $2i+1$ ⁠, and ⌊*i*/2⌋, respectively, in an array starting from ⁠ 1 ⁠.
[src:binomial-heap/heap-data-structure] This simple indexing scheme makes it efficient to walk "up" or "down" the tree.
[src:binomial-heap/heap-data-structure] Balancing a heap is done by sift-up or sift-down operations (swapping elements which are out of order).
[src:binomial-heap/heap-data-structure] As we can build a heap from an array without requiring extra memory (for the nodes, for example), heapsort can be used to sort an array in-place.
[src:binomial-heap/heap-data-structure] After an element is inserted into or deleted from a heap, the heap property may be violated, and the heap must be re-balanced by swapping elements within the array.
[src:binomial-heap/heap-data-structure] This is faster than a sequence of consecutive insertions into an originally empty heap, which is log-linear.
[src:binomial-heap/heap-data-structure] *make-heap* is the operation of building a heap from a sequence of *n* unsorted elements.
[src:binomial-heap/heap-data-structure] It can be done in *Θ*(*n*) time whenever *meld* runs in *O*(log *n*) time (where both complexities can be amortized).
[src:binomial-heap/heap-data-structure] Another algorithm achieves *Θ*(*n*) for binary heaps.
[src:binomial-heap/heap-data-structure] For persistent heaps (not supporting *increase-key*), a generic transformation reduces the cost of *meld* to that of *insert*, while the new cost of *delete-max* is the sum of the old costs of *delete-max* and *meld*.
[src:binomial-heap/heap-data-structure] Here, it makes *meld* run in *Θ*(1) time (amortized, if the cost of *insert* is) while *delete-max* still runs in *O*(log *n*).
[src:binomial-heap/heap-data-structure] The Brodal-Okasaki queue is a persistent data structure achieving the same optimum, except that *increase-key* is not supported.
[src:binomial-heap/heap-data-structure] The heap data structure has many applications.
[src:binomial-heap/priority-queue] In computer science, a **priority queue** is an abstract data type similar to a regular queue where each element has an associated priority determining its order of service.
[src:binomial-heap/priority-queue] Priority queue serves highest priority items first.
[src:binomial-heap/priority-queue] Priority values have to be instances of an ordered data type, and higher priority can be given either to the lesser or to the greater values with respect to the given order relation.
[src:binomial-heap/priority-queue] For example, in the Java standard library, the PriorityQueue class considers the lowest element with respect to their order as having the highest priority.
[src:binomial-heap/priority-queue] While priority queues are often implemented using heaps, they are conceptually distinct.
[src:binomial-heap/priority-queue] A priority queue can be implemented with a heap or with other methods; just as a list can be implemented with a linked list or with an array.
[src:binomial-heap/priority-queue] Stacks and queues can be implemented as particular kinds of priority queues, with the priority determined by the order in which the elements are inserted.
[src:binomial-heap/priority-queue] In a stack, the priority of each inserted element is monotonically increasing; thus, the last element inserted is always the first retrieved.
[src:binomial-heap/priority-queue] In a queue, the priority of each inserted element is monotonically decreasing; thus, the first element inserted is always the first retrieved.
[src:binomial-heap/priority-queue] In some implementations, if two elements have the same priority, they are served in the same order in which they were enqueued.
[src:binomial-heap/priority-queue] In other implementations, the order of elements with the same priority is undefined.
[src:binomial-heap/priority-queue] One can create a simple, but inefficient priority queue in a number of ways.
[src:binomial-heap/priority-queue] These naive implementations can demonstrate the expected behaviour of a priority queue in a simpler manner.
[src:binomial-heap/priority-queue] To improve performance, priority queues are typically based on a heap, giving $O(\log n)$ performance for inserts and removals, and $O(n)$ to build the heap initially from a set of n elements.
[src:binomial-heap/priority-queue] Variants of the basic heap data structure such as pairing heaps or Fibonacci heaps can provide better bounds for some operations.
[src:binomial-heap/priority-queue] From a space-complexity standpoint, using self-balancing binary search tree with linked list takes more storage, since it requires storing extra references to other nodes.
[src:binomial-heap/priority-queue] From a computational-complexity standpoint, priority queues are congruent to sorting algorithms.
[src:binomial-heap/priority-queue] The section on the equivalence of priority queues and sorting algorithms, below, describes how efficient sorting algorithms can create efficient priority queues.
[src:binomial-heap/priority-queue] There are several specialized heap data structures that either supply additional operations or outperform heap-based implementations for specific types of keys, specifically integer keys.
[src:binomial-heap/priority-queue] For applications that do many "peek" operations for every "`extract-min`" operation, the time complexity for peek actions can be reduced to $O(1)$ in all tree and heap implementations by caching the highest priority element after every insertion and removal.
[src:binomial-heap/priority-queue] For insertion, this adds at most a constant cost, since the newly inserted element is compared only to the previously cached minimum element.
[src:binomial-heap/priority-queue] For deletion, this at most adds an additional "peek" cost, which is typically cheaper than the deletion cost, so overall time complexity is not significantly impacted.
[src:binomial-heap/priority-queue] Monotone priority queues are specialized queues that are optimized for the case where no item is ever inserted that has a lower priority (in the case of min-heap) than any item previously extracted.
[src:binomial-heap/priority-queue] This restriction is met by several practical applications of priority queues.
[src:binomial-heap/priority-queue] The semantics of priority queues naturally suggest a sorting method: insert all the elements to be sorted into a priority queue, and sequentially remove them; they will come out in sorted order.
[src:binomial-heap/priority-queue] This is actually the procedure used by several sorting algorithms, once the layer of abstraction provided by the priority queue is removed.
[src:binomial-heap/priority-queue] A sorting algorithm can also be used to implement a priority queue.
[src:binomial-heap/priority-queue] For example, if one has an $O(n\log n)$ sort algorithm, one can create a priority queue with $O(1)$ pulling and $O(\log n)$ insertion.
[src:binomial-heap/priority-queue] A priority queue is often considered to be a "container data structure".
[src:binomial-heap/priority-queue] The Standard Template Library (STL), and the C++ 1998 standard, specifies std::priority_queue as one of the STL container adaptor class templates.
[src:binomial-heap/priority-queue] However, it does not specify how two elements with same priority should be served, and indeed, common implementations will not return them according to their order in the queue.
[src:binomial-heap/priority-queue] Unlike actual STL containers, it does not allow iteration of its elements (it strictly adheres to its abstract data type definition).
[src:binomial-heap/priority-queue] STL also has utility functions for manipulating another random-access container as a binary max-heap.
[src:binomial-heap/priority-queue] The Boost libraries also have an implementation in the library heap.
[src:binomial-heap/priority-queue] Python's heapq module implements a binary min-heap on top of a list.
[src:binomial-heap/priority-queue] Java's library contains a `PriorityQueue` (`java.util.PriorityQueue`) class, which implements a min-priority-queue as a binary heap.
[src:binomial-heap/priority-queue] .NET's library contains a System.Collections.Generic.PriorityQueue class, which implements an array-backed, quaternary min-heap.
[src:binomial-heap/priority-queue] Scala's library contains a scala.collection.mutable.PriorityQueue class, which implements a max-priority-queue.
[src:binomial-heap/priority-queue] Go's library contains a container/heap module, which implements a min-heap on top of any compatible data structure.
[src:binomial-heap/priority-queue] Rust's standard library contains a std::collections::BinaryHeap struct, which implements a priority queue with a binary heap.
[src:binomial-heap/priority-queue] The Standard PHP Library extension contains the class SplPriorityQueue.
[src:binomial-heap/priority-queue] Apple's Core Foundation framework contains a CFBinaryHeap structure, which implements a min-heap.
[src:binomial-heap/priority-queue] Priority queuing can be used to manage limited resources such as bandwidth on a transmission line from a network router.
[src:binomial-heap/priority-queue] In the event of outgoing traffic queuing due to insufficient bandwidth, all other queues can be halted to send the traffic from the highest priority queue upon arrival.
[src:binomial-heap/priority-queue] This ensures that the prioritized traffic (such as real-time traffic, e.g. an RTP stream of a VoIP connection) is forwarded with the least delay and the least likelihood of being rejected due to a queue reaching its maximum capacity.
[src:binomial-heap/priority-queue] All other traffic can be handled when the highest priority queue is empty.
[src:binomial-heap/priority-queue] Another approach used is to send disproportionately more traffic from higher priority queues.
[src:binomial-heap/priority-queue] Many modern protocols for local area networks also include the concept of priority queues at the media access control (MAC) sub-layer to ensure that high-priority applications (such as VoIP or IPTV) experience lower latency than other applications which can be served with best-effort service.
[src:binomial-heap/priority-queue] Examples include IEEE 802.11e (an amendment to IEEE 802.11 which provides quality of service) and ITU-T G.hn (a standard for high-speed local area network using existing home wiring (power lines, phone lines and coaxial cables).
[src:binomial-heap/priority-queue] Usually a limitation (policer) is set to limit the bandwidth that traffic from the highest priority queue can take, in order to prevent high priority packets from choking off all other traffic.
[src:binomial-heap/priority-queue] This limit is usually never reached due to high level control instances such as the Cisco Callmanager, which can be programmed to inhibit calls which would exceed the programmed bandwidth limit.
[src:binomial-heap/priority-queue] Another use of a priority queue is to manage the events in a discrete event simulation.
[src:binomial-heap/priority-queue] The events are added to the queue with their simulation time used as the priority.
[src:binomial-heap/priority-queue] The execution of the simulation proceeds by repeatedly pulling the top of the queue and executing the event thereon.
[src:binomial-heap/priority-queue] When the graph is stored in the form of adjacency list or matrix, priority queue can be used to extract minimum efficiently when implementing Dijkstra's algorithm, although one also needs the ability to alter the priority of a particular vertex in the priority queue efficiently.
[src:binomial-heap/priority-queue] If instead, a graph is stored as node objects, and priority-node pairs are inserted into a heap, altering the priority of a particular vertex is not necessary if one tracks visited nodes.
[src:binomial-heap/priority-queue] Once a node is visited, if it comes up in the heap again (having had a lower priority number associated with it earlier), it is popped-off and ignored.
[src:binomial-heap/priority-queue] Huffman coding requires one to repeatedly obtain the two lowest-frequency trees.
[src:binomial-heap/priority-queue] A priority queue is one method of doing this.
[src:binomial-heap/priority-queue] Best-first search algorithms, like the A* search algorithm, find the shortest path between two vertices or nodes of a weighted graph, trying out the most promising routes first.
[src:binomial-heap/priority-queue] A priority queue (also known as the *fringe*) is used to keep track of unexplored routes; the one for which the estimate (a lower bound in the case of A*) of the total path length is smallest is given highest priority.
[src:binomial-heap/priority-queue] If memory limitations make best-first search impractical, variants like the SMA* algorithm can be used instead, with a double-ended priority queue to allow removal of low-priority items.
[src:binomial-heap/priority-queue] The Real-time Optimally Adapting Meshes (ROAM) algorithm computes a dynamically changing triangulation of a terrain.
[src:binomial-heap/priority-queue] It works by splitting triangles where more detail is needed and merging them where less detail is needed.
[src:binomial-heap/priority-queue] The algorithm assigns each triangle in the terrain a priority, usually related to the error decrease if that triangle would be split.
[src:binomial-heap/priority-queue] The algorithm uses two priority queues, one for triangles that can be split and another for triangles that can be merged.
[src:binomial-heap/priority-queue] In each step the triangle from the split queue with the highest priority is split, or the triangle from the merge queue with the lowest priority is merged with its neighbours.
[src:binomial-heap/priority-queue] Using min heap priority queue in Prim's algorithm to find the minimum spanning tree of a connected and undirected graph, one can achieve a good running time.
[src:binomial-heap/priority-queue] This min heap priority queue uses the min heap data structure which supports operations such as `insert`, `minimum`, `extract-min`, `decrease-key`.
[src:binomial-heap/priority-queue] In this implementation, the weight of the edges is used to decide the priority of the vertices.
[src:binomial-heap/priority-queue] Lower the weight, higher the priority and higher the weight, lower the priority.
[src:binomial-heap/priority-queue] Parallelization can be used to speed up priority queues, but requires some changes to the priority queue interface.
[src:binomial-heap/priority-queue] The reason for such changes is that a sequential update usually only has ${\textstyle O(1)}$ or ${\textstyle O(\log n)}$ cost, and there is no practical gain to parallelize such an operation.
[src:binomial-heap/priority-queue] One possible change is to allow the concurrent access of multiple processors to the same priority queue.
[src:binomial-heap/priority-queue] The second possible change is to allow batch operations that work on ${\textstyle k}$ elements, instead of just one element.
[src:binomial-heap/priority-queue] For example, `extractMin` will remove the first ${\textstyle k}$ elements with the highest priority.
[src:binomial-heap/priority-queue] If the priority queue allows concurrent access, multiple processes can perform operations concurrently on that priority queue.
[src:binomial-heap/priority-queue] First of all, the definition of the semantics of the individual operations is no longer obvious.
[src:binomial-heap/priority-queue] For example, if two processes want to extract the element with the highest priority, should they get the same element or different ones?
[src:binomial-heap/priority-queue] This restricts parallelism on the level of the program using the priority queue.
[src:binomial-heap/priority-queue] In addition, because multiple processes have access to the same element, this leads to contention.
[src:binomial-heap/priority-queue] The concurrent access to a priority queue can be implemented on a Concurrent Read, Concurrent Write (CRCW) PRAM model.
[src:binomial-heap/priority-queue] In the following the priority queue is implemented as a skip list.
[src:binomial-heap/priority-queue] In addition, an atomic synchronization primitive, CAS, is used to make the skip list lock-free.
[src:binomial-heap/priority-queue] The nodes of the skip list consists of a unique key, a priority, an array of pointers, for each level, to the next nodes and a `delete` mark.
[src:binomial-heap/priority-queue] The `delete` mark marks if the node is about to be deleted by a process.
[src:binomial-heap/priority-queue] This ensures that other processes can react to the deletion appropriately.
[src:binomial-heap/priority-queue] If the concurrent access to a priority queue is allowed, conflicts may arise between two processes.
[src:binomial-heap/priority-queue] For example, a conflict arises if one process is trying to insert a new node, but at the same time another process is about to delete the predecessor of that node.
[src:binomial-heap/priority-queue] There is a risk that the new node is added to the skip list, yet it is not longer reachable.
[src:binomial-heap/priority-queue] In this setting, operations on a priority queue is generalized to a batch of ${\textstyle k}$ elements.
[src:binomial-heap/priority-queue] For instance, `k_extract-min` deletes the ${\textstyle k}$ smallest elements of the priority queue and returns those.
[src:binomial-heap/priority-queue] In a shared-memory setting, the parallel priority queue can be easily implemented using parallel binary search trees and join-based tree algorithms.
[src:binomial-heap/priority-queue] In particular, `k_extract-min` corresponds to a *split* on the binary search tree that has ${\textstyle O(\log n)}$ cost and yields a tree that contains the ${\textstyle k}$ smallest elements.
[src:binomial-heap/priority-queue] `k_insert` can be applied by a *union* of the original priority queue and the batch of insertions.
[src:binomial-heap/priority-queue] If the batch is already sorted by the key, `k_insert` has ${\textstyle O(k\log(1+{\frac {n}{k}}))}$ cost.
[src:binomial-heap/priority-queue] Otherwise, we need to first sort the batch, so the cost will be ${\textstyle O(k\log(1+{\frac {n}{k}})+k\log k)=O(k\log n)}$ .
[src:binomial-heap/priority-queue] Other operations for priority queue can be applied similarly.
[src:binomial-heap/priority-queue] For instance, `k_decrease-key` can be done by first applying `difference` and then `union`, which first deletes the elements and then inserts them back with the updated keys.
[src:binomial-heap/priority-queue] All these operations are highly parallel, and the theoretical and practical efficiency can be found in related research papers.
[src:binomial-heap/priority-queue] The rest of this section discusses a queue-based algorithm on distributed memory.
[src:binomial-heap/priority-queue] We assume each processor has its own local memory and a local (sequential) priority queue.
[src:binomial-heap/priority-queue] The elements of the global (parallel) priority queue are distributed across all processors.
[src:binomial-heap/priority-queue] A `k_insert` operation assigns the elements uniformly random to the processors which insert the elements into their local queues.
[src:binomial-heap/priority-queue] Note that single elements can still be inserted into the queue.
[src:binomial-heap/priority-queue] Using this strategy the global smallest elements are in the union of the local smallest elements of every processor with high probability.
[src:binomial-heap/priority-queue] Thus each processor holds a representative part of the global priority queue.
[src:binomial-heap/priority-queue] This property is used when `k_extract-min` is executed, as the smallest ${\textstyle m}$ elements of each local queue are removed and collected in a result set.
[src:binomial-heap/priority-queue] The elements in the result set are still associated with their original processor.
[src:binomial-heap/priority-queue] The number of elements ${\textstyle m}$ that is removed from each local queue depends on ${\textstyle k}$ and the number of processors ${\textstyle p}$ .
[src:binomial-heap/priority-queue] By parallel selection the ${\textstyle k}$ smallest elements of the result set are determined.
[src:binomial-heap/priority-queue] With high probability these are the global ${\textstyle k}$ smallest elements.
[src:binomial-heap/priority-queue] If not, ${\textstyle m}$ elements are again removed from each local queue and put into the result set.
[src:binomial-heap/priority-queue] This is done until the global ${\textstyle k}$ smallest elements are in the result set.
[src:binomial-heap/priority-queue] Now these ${\textstyle k}$ elements can be returned.
[src:binomial-heap/priority-queue] All other elements of the result set are inserted back into their local queues.
[src:binomial-heap/priority-queue] The running time of `k_extract-min` is expected ${\textstyle O({\frac {k}{p}}\log(n))}$ , where ${\textstyle k=\Omega (p\cdot \log(p))}$ and ${\textstyle n}$ is the size of the priority queue.
[src:binomial-heap/priority-queue] The priority queue can be further improved by not moving the remaining elements of the result set directly back into the local queues after a `k_extract-min` operation.
[src:binomial-heap/priority-queue] This saves moving elements back and forth all the time between the result set and the local queues.
[src:binomial-heap/priority-queue] By removing several elements at once a considerable speedup can be reached.
[src:binomial-heap/priority-queue] But not all algorithms can use this kind of priority queue.
[src:binomial-heap/priority-queue] Dijkstra's algorithm for example can not work on several nodes at once.
[src:binomial-heap/priority-queue] The algorithm takes the node with the smallest distance from the priority queue and calculates new distances for all its neighbor nodes.
[src:binomial-heap/priority-queue] If you would take out ${\textstyle k}$ nodes, working at one node could change the distance of another one of the ${\textstyle k}$ nodes.
[src:binomial-heap/priority-queue] So using k-element operations destroys the label setting property of Dijkstra's algorithm.
